\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
\par Incantations function like spells, except a character need not be a spellcaster to cast them. Anyone can cast an incantation simply by performing the correct ritual gestures and phrases. Incantations don\rquote t use spell slots, so they don\rquote 
t have to be prepared ahead of time, and there\rquote 
s no limit on the number of times one can cast an incantation per day. Since they do not use up spell slots, incantations cannot be improved using metamagic feats. Finally, incantations generally have more powerful, far-rea
ching effects than even 5th-level spells.
\par There is, of course, a catch. Incantations take much longer to cast than normal spells. Success with an incantation is never assured, and the consequences for failure can be dramatic. The most powerful incantations
 can require rituals involving multiple participants, strange or expensive material components, or other aspects that make them difficult to cast.
\par }{\cf0 
\par Discovering Incantations
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The instructions for performing incantations are generally found in various obscure tomes. Such books are filled with \'93magic spells,\'94
 and most of them are utterly bogus. But hidden among the dross is the real stuff, and discerning whether an incantation found in a book will actually work is a matter for experts in arcane lore.
\par Finding a set of instructions for a particular incantation requires a successful Research check with a DC equal to the Knowledge (arcane lore) DC for the incantation \endash 10. Just learning of the existence of a particular incantation is an easie
r Research check, with a DC equal to the Knowledge (arcane lore) DC \endash 15.
\par }{\b\fs22\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Casting an Incantation
\par }{\fs20\cf0 At its core, casting an incantation means having the required incantation components, then succeeding at a number of Knowledge (arcane lore) checks during the incantation\rquote 
s casting time. Each incantation lists how many Knowledge (arcane lore) checks are required to cast the incantation successfully.
\par Unless otherwise specified, the caster makes Knowledge (arcane lore) checks every 10 minutes. Failing a Knowledge (arcane lore) check doesn\rquote 
t mean that the entire incantation is a failure, just that the previous 10 minutes have been wasted. However, if you fail two Knowledge (arcane lore) checks in a row, the incantation immediately fails. The consequences for failure
 are detailed in the description of the specific incantation. Even if the incantation fails, material components and experience points are still lost and the backlash still takes effect.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Incantation Components
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Most incantations require components not unlik
e spells, including verbal, somatic, focus, and material components. In addition, some require secondary casters (abbreviated SC), cause some sort of backlash (abbreviated B), or cost the caster some experience points (abbreviated XP).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Secondary Casters
\par }{\fs20\cf0 So
me incantations require multiple participants to cast successfully. These secondary casters (abbreviated SC) are indispensable to the success of the spell. No matter how many people are gathered in the dark room, chanting with candles, only one character
\emdash generally the one with the highest Knowledge (arcane lore) check\emdash is the primary caster who\rquote ll make the relevant checks. Secondary casters can\rquote 
t help the primary caster with the Aid Another rules, but their presence is required for certain aspects of the rit
ual nonetheless. If an incantation requires some other skill check, any of the secondary casters can make that check if they have a higher bonus than the primary caster. Even if you\rquote 
re not a required caster of the spell, you can step in and make the non-Knowledge check if you\rquote re better at the relevant skill than the actual caster. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Backlash
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Some spells damage or drain the caster in some way. They have a backlash component, generally damage, negative levels, or some other condition. The caster takes the backlash regardless of the success or failure of the spell.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saves and Spell Resistance
\par }{\fs20\cf0 If the incantation allows a save, the formula to calculate it is included in the spell\rquote s description. For checks to overcome spell resistance, divide the incantation\rquote 
s Knowledge (arcane lore) DC by 2 to get the effective caster level for the spell resistance check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Incantations as Spell-Like Abilities
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Some creatures have spell-like abilities that duplicate the effects of incantations. There\rquote s no chance of failure and no backlash for such spell-like abilities, which don\rquote 
t require components of any kind and take only an attack action to activate.
\par }{\b\fs22\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Failed Incantations
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Each incantation has its own consequences for failure (two failed skill checks in a row). In general, they can be divided into the following categories.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attack: }{\fs20\cf0 A creature is called from elsewhere to battle the caster (and often any bystanders and secondary casters). The incantation\rquote s description tells the GM what Challenge Rating the creature should have, how
 it behaves, and how long it persists.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Augment: }{\fs20\cf0 The incantation was supposed to weaken or destroy its target, but it makes it more powerful instead. A damaging spell might heal its target or cause it to grow in size, for example.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Betrayal: }{\fs20\cf0 The incantation 
seemingly succeeds, but the subject of the incantation (or in rare cases the caster) loses all allegiances and gains their opposites. In general, the subject now hates all it loved before the incantation. The subject may keep its new allegiances a secret.
 Whenever a character attempts an incantation with a chance of betrayal failure, the GM should make the relevant die rolls in secret. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 The simplest consequence of failure, damage is dealt to the caster or the target, depending on the incantation.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Death: }{\fs20\cf0 Someone\emdash usually the caster or the target\emdash dies. Depending on the incantation, a successful saving throw may avoid the effect of failure.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Delusion: }{\fs20\cf0 The caster believes the incantation had the desired effect, but in fact it had no effect or a very different one.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Falsehood: }{\fs20\cf0 
Common with divinations, the incantation delivers false results to the caster, but the caster believes the results are true. Whenever a character attempts an incantation with a chance of falsehood failure, the GM should make the relevan
t die rolls in secret.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Hostile Spell: }{\fs20\cf0 The caster of the incantation is targeted by a harmful spell or incantation. The spell description specifies the specific spell or incantation, save DC, and so on. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Mirrorcast: }{\fs20\cf0 The spell has the opposite effect of that intended.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Reversal: }{\fs20\cf0 The spell targets the caster, rather than the intended target of the incantation.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Baleful Polymorph
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Transmutation
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 41, 6 successes, and Knowledge (earth and life sciences), 1 success; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 
V, S, M, F, SC; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time: }{\fs20\cf0 70 minutes (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 Touch; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Target: }{\fs20\cf0 Helpless creature touched; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 Permanent; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }
{\fs20\cf0 Fortitude negates (DC 17 + caster\rquote s Cha modifier) and see text; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 Yes
\par As the }{\i\fs20\cf0 polymorph }{\fs20\cf0 incantation, except that you change the subject into a Small or smaller animal of no more than 1 HD (such as a dog, lizard, monkey, toad, or viper). If the new form would prove fatal to
 the creature (such as polymorphing a landbound target into a fish), the subject gets a +4 bonus on the save. If the incantation succeeds, the target must also make a Will save. If this second save fails, the creature gains the Intelligence, Wisdom, and C
harisma scores of its new form. It still retains its class and level, hit points, base attack bonus, base save bonuses, allegiances, extraordinary abilities, supernatural abilities, and spell-like abilities, as well as any spellcasting ability possessed.

\par Note that incorporeal or gaseous creatures are immune to being polymorphed, and a shapeshifter (such as a werewolf) can revert to its natural form as a move action. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Material Component: }{\fs20\cf0 Laboratory equipment and alchemical supplies (purchase DC 25).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Focus: }{\fs20\cf0 Pa
rt of the kind of creature that the target will turn into, such as a hair, scale, or feather. If you have a living, helpless creature that can serve as a model for the target creature, you gain a +2 bonus on the Knowledge (arcane lore) checks required for
 this incantation.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Secondary Casters: }{\fs20\cf0 12 required (not including the primary caster).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Reversal on all secondary casters, using the same saving throw DC.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Bibliolalia
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Divination
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 33, 6 successes; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 V, S, F, XP; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time: }{\fs20\cf0 
60 minutes (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 Personal; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Target: }{\fs20\cf0 You; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 Instantaneous; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }{\fs20\cf0 None; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 No
\par The }{\i\fs20\cf0 bibliolalia }{\fs20\cf0 incantation puts you in an oracular trance as you pore through books in a library. At the incantation\rquote 
s conclusion, you uncover lore about an important person, place, or thing beyond the limits of mundane research.
\par The information gleaned through a }{\i\fs20\cf0 bibliolalia }{\fs20\cf0 incantation isn\rquote 
t necessarily known to anyone, and it may not be in any of the books in the library. Nonetheless, something within the books triggers the burst of magical inspiration that reveals the information.
\par No set of rules can adequately describe how much information the }{\i\fs20\cf0 bibliolalia }{\fs20\cf0 incantation provides. If you have the item or person at hand, you\rquote ll learn more than if you just have a name or a cryptic clue. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Focus: }{\fs20\cf0 A large library with at least a token occult section (purchase DC 25).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Experience Point Cost: }{\fs20\cf0 200 XP.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Falsehood. The }{\i\fs20\cf0 bibliolalia }{\fs20\cf0 incantation reveals information that seems accurate, but is actively misleading.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Body Double
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Conjuration (Creation)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 39, 6 successes (and see text) and Disguise DC 39, 1 success; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 
V, S, M (see text), XP; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time: }{\fs20\cf0 7 hours (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 Touch; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Effect: }{\fs20\cf0 One duplicate creature; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 12 days; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }
{\fs20\cf0 None; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 No
\par The }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 incantation creates 
a duplicate of any creature formed from mystic clay, with alchemical blood and an eldritch life of its own. At first glance, the duplicate appears to be exactly the same as the creature you modeled it after, but there are differences: The }{\i\fs20\cf0 
body double }{\fs20\cf0 has o
nly half the level or Hit Dice (which affects its skills, feats, and class features). It has the surface mannerisms and personality of the real creature, but its Intelligence, Wisdom, and Charisma scores are all 5. Creatures familiar with the original mig
h
t detect the ruse with a successful Spot check. You must make a Disguise check when you cast the incantation to determine how good the likeness is, and this Disguise check sets the DC for Spot checks (to notice imperfections in the duplication) and Sense 
Motive checks (to discern that the }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 is behaving oddly).
\par At all times the }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 remains under your absolute command. No special telepathic link exists, so command must be exercised in some other manner. The }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 has no ability to beco
me more powerful. It cannot earn experience points. If destroyed, it reverts to clay and melts into a vaguely humanoid lump within 1 minute. The }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 doesn\rquote 
t naturally heal and responds to neither conventional medicine nor natural healing. A complex process requiring at least one day, materials (purchase DC 5 + 1 per hit point), and a fully equipped magical laboratory can repair damage to the }{\i\fs20\cf0 
body double}{\fs20\cf0 .
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Material Component: }{\fs20\cf0 The spell is cast over an elaborate clay simulacrum of the creature to be du
plicated, and some piece of the creature (a hair or fingernail, for instance) must be placed within the clay. Additionally, the incantation requires rare earths and unguents (purchase DC 30).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 XP Cost: }{\fs20\cf0 1,000 XP.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Betrayal. The }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{\fs20\cf0 has allegiances opposite the original creature and a pathological hatred of both the original creature and the caster. Furthermore, the }{\i\fs20\cf0 body double }{
\fs20\cf0 isn\rquote t under the command of the caster, although it may play along for a while while it learns about its new enemies.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Caduceus
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Conjuration (Healing)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 31, 4 successes, and Treat Injury DC 31, 2 success; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 V, S, F; }{\b\fs20\cf0 
Casting Time: }{\fs20\cf0 6 hours (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 Touch; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Target: }{\fs20\cf0 Living creature; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 Instantaneous; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }{\fs20\cf0 Will negates (harmless); }{
\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 Yes (harmless)
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Caduceus }{\fs20\cf0 enables you to channel magic into a creature to wipe away injury and afflictions. It immediately ends any and all of the following adv
erse conditions affecting the target: temporary ability damage (but not permanent ability drain), blindness (including dazzled effects), confusion or insanity, daze, deafness, fatigue, exhaustion, feeblemindedness, nausea, and poison. It also cures up to 
150 points of damage. A single casting of the incantation is enough to simultaneously achieve all these effects.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Caduceus }{\fs20\cf0 also removes negative levels, but it does not restore permanently drained levels.
\par The }{\i\fs20\cf0 caduceus }{\fs20\cf0 incantation has no effect on undead or constructs.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Focus: }{\fs20\cf0 Medical equipment found in a hospital emergency room (purchase DC 25).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Death. Target must succeed at a Fortitude save (DC 15) or die. If the save succeeds, the target is reduced to \endash 1 hit points, unless he was already below that.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Cast into Shadow
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Abjuration
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 33, 6 successes (see text); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 V, S, M, XP, B; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time: }{
\fs20\cf0 1 hour (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 55 ft.; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Target: }{\fs20\cf0 One or more outsiders, no two of which can be more than 30 ft. apart; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 Permanent; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }{
\fs20\cf0 Fortitude negates (DC 17 + caster\rquote s Cha modifier) and see text; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 Yes
\par The }{\i\fs20\cf0 cast into Shadow }{\fs20\cf0 incantation enables you to force outsiders (usually, but not always, fien
ds) away from the world you know, trapping them in some distant dimension. Up to 2 HD of creatures per caster level can be sent away in this fashion.
\par To target a creature, you must present at least one object or substance that it hates, fears, or otherwise opposes.
\par If you successfully overcome the target\rquote s spell resistance, and the target fails its save, the target disappears. In general, targets never find their way back from beyond Shadow\emdash or if they do, they don\rquote 
t remember their previous time here.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Options: }{\fs20\cf0 If the target or targets are all helpless, the DC for the incantation is reduced by \endash 6. At the GM\rquote 
s option, certain rare items might work twice as well (each providing +2 against spell resistance and +4 on the spell\rquote s DC).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Material Component: }{\fs20\cf0 An object the creature hates, fears, or opposes. Discovering such an item may require a Research check.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Experience Point Cost: }{\fs20\cf0 1,000 XP.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Backlash: }{\fs20\cf0 Caster is exhausted. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Attack from an outsider of the same allegiance. The attacking outsider has a Challenge Rating equal to the average party level +1. It attacks the caster within a few rounds of the incantation\rquote 
s failure. It has been brought to this world by the failed incantation, so it may retreat and try to make a home for itself here. It will always bear a 
grudge against the caster for bringing it here, however, and it is a potential source of later mischief.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\cf0 Control Weather
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Evocation
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Skill Check: }{\fs20\cf0 Knowledge (arcane lore) DC 34, 6 successes; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Failure: }{\fs20\cf0 Two consecutive failed skill checks; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components: }{\fs20\cf0 V, S, SC; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time: }{\fs20\cf0 
60 minutes (minimum); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range: }{\fs20\cf0 Two miles; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Area: }{\fs20\cf0 Two-mile-radius circle, centered on you; }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration: }{\fs20\cf0 24 hours (D); }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }{\fs20\cf0 None; }{\b\fs20\cf0 
Spell Resistance: }{\fs20\cf0 No
\par You change the weather in the local area. It takes 10 minutes for the effects to manifest
 after the incantation is completed. The current, natural weather conditions are determined by the GM. You can call forth weather appropriate to the climate and season of the area you are in.
